The isotope labeling experiment, conducted in a K2HPO4 solution saturated with 13CO, gave a complete splitting of the 1H NMR singlet peak at δ = 3.34 ppm (CH3 protons) to a doublet peak (jC–H = 142 Hz)50, demonstrating that CO is the source for the observed methanol production (Fig. 2d). Moreover, no CH3OH could be detected in similar experiments where CoPc/MWCNT was replaced by metal-free H2Pc molecule adsorbed on MWCNTs (H2Pc/MWCNT) and single-Co-atom catalyst derived from calcination (Supplementary Fig. 7). It suggests that the well-defined coordination environment of the Co atom in CoPc molecule should be responsible for the evolution of methanol from CORR. As displayed in Supplementary Fig. 8, the FECH3OH\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
